{"title_page": "Michael O'Brien (Ohio politician)", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Michael O'Brien\n| image        = \n| order1       = Member of the<br>[[Ohio House of Representatives]]<br>from the 64th district\n| term_start1  = January 3, 2015\n| term_end1    = \n| predecessor1 = [[Tom Letson]]\n| successor1   = \n<!--Personal data-->\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1955|06|18}}\n| birth_place  = \n| party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| residence    = [[Warren, Ohio]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| education    =John F. Kennedy High School\n| alma_mater   =[[Youngstown State University]]\n}}\n'''Michael J. O'Brien''' (born June 18, 1955) is the Representative of the 64th district of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]]. O'Brien is a lifelong resident of the [[Mahoning Valley]] and graduate from John F. Kennedy High School as well as [[Youngstown State University]].  O'Brien served on Warren City Council from 1983 to 1993 before being elected as a Trumbull County Commissioner in 1994.  He served as a commissioner for ten years before being elected Mayor of Warren in 2005, serving until 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.electmichaelobrien.com/?page_id=12 |title=About Mike O'Brien |accessdate=2014-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209055527/http://www.electmichaelobrien.com/?page_id=12 |archive-date=2014-12-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{Self-published source|date=June 2017}}  O'Brien announced in early 2014 that he would seek a seat in the [[Ohio House of Representatives]] to replace [[Tom Letson]] who was term-limited.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://wkbn.com/2014/01/23/former-warren-mayor-seeks-state-post/ |title=Former Warren mayor seeks state post |work=WKBN |location=Youngstown |date=2014-01-23 |accessdate=2014-12-06 }}</ref> He would win a three-way primary race with 60% of the vote for the Democratic nomination.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vindy.com/news/2014/may/07/trumbull-voters-tap-two-obriens-for-seat/ |title=Mike O\u2019Brien gets primary nod for 64th House |work=Vindicator |location=Youngstown |date=2014-05-07 |accessdate=2014-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110190626/http://www.vindy.com/news/2014/may/07/trumbull-voters-tap-two-obriens-for-seat/ |archive-date=2019-01-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He faced former Republican state Representative [[Randy Law]] in the general election, in what became a very tight race. He defeated Law 49%-44% to take the seat.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://wytv.com/2014/11/04/obrien-to-represent-ohios-64th-district-2/ |title=O\u2019Brien to represent Ohio\u2019s 64th district |work=WYTV |location=Youngstown |date=2014-11-04 |accessdate=2014-12-06 }}</ref> His district includes half of [[Trumbull County, Ohio|Trumbull County]] and the southern portion of [[Ashtabula County, Ohio|Ashtabula County]].\n\nIn 2005, Mayor Michael J. O'Brien was fined by the Ohio Ethics Committee for mishandling campaign contributions.\n\n\"According to a complaint filed in July by Victor V. Vigluicci, special prosecutor in Trumbull County, O'Brien from 2000 to 2003 received $2,035 in campaign contributions that were deposited into the joint personal checking account with his wife, or the personal savings of son Dominic and Louise O'Brien.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vindy.com/news/2005/sep/02/campaign-finance-obrien-fined-in-elections/?print|title=CAMPAIGN FINANCE O'Brien fined in elections violation|website=www.vindy.com|access-date=2016-09-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009. Mayor O'Brien proposed laying off 20 police officers and 11 firefighters in order to balance the Warren City budget.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wfmj.com/story/9368716/mayor-announces-warren-city-layoffs|title=Mayor Announces Warren City Layoffs|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref> This was after he hired 48 new city employees during his first term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tribtoday.com/page/content.detail/id/523523/Hiring-in-city-not-a-logical-practice.html?nav=5007|title=Hiring in city not a logical practice - TribToday.com - News, Sports, Jobs, Community Information -  Tribune Chronicle - Warren, OH|website=www.tribtoday.com|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref>\n\n\"As late as April 2008, when financial devastation was as clear as a bell, O'Brien hired four police officers, including Councilwoman Susan Hartman's son. A few months later they received their layoff notices.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tribtoday.com/page/content.detail/id/523523/Hiring-in-city-not-a-logical-practice.html?nav=5007|title=Hiring in city not a logical practice - TribToday.com - News, Sports, Jobs, Community Information -  Tribune Chronicle - Warren, OH|website=www.tribtoday.com|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Links==\n*[https://www.facebook.com/electmichaelobrien campaign Facebook page]\n*[http://www.electmichaelobrien.com/ campaign site]\n{{Members of the Ohio House of Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:OBrien, Michael}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Ohio Democrats]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Warren, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Youngstown State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio city council members]]\n[[Category:County commissioners in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Ohio]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-OHRepresentative-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Michael O'Brien\n| image        = \n| order1       = Member of the<br>[[Ohio House of Representatives]]<br>from the 64th district\n| term_start1  = January 3, 2015\n| term_end1    = \n| predecessor1 = [[Tom Letson]]\n| successor1   = \n<!--Personal data-->\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1955|06|18}}\n| birth_place  = \n| party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| residence    = [[Warren, Ohio]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| education    =John F. Kennedy High School\n| alma_mater   =[[Youngstown State University]]\n}}\n'''Michael J. O'Brien''' (born June 18, 1955) is the Representative of the 64th district of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]]. O'Brien is a lifelong resident of the [[Mahoning Valley]] and graduate from John F. Kennedy High School as well as [[Youngstown State University]].  O'Brien served on Warren City Council from 1983 to 1993 before being elected as a Trumbull County Commissioner in 1994.  He served as a commissioner for ten years before being elected Mayor of Warren in 2005, serving until 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.electmichaelobrien.com/?page_id=12 |title=About Mike O'Brien |accessdate=2014-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209055527/http://www.electmichaelobrien.com/?page_id=12 |archive-date=2014-12-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{Self-published source|date=June 2017}}  O'Brien announced in early 2014 that he would seek a seat in the [[Ohio House of Representatives]] to replace [[Tom Letson]] who was term-limited.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://wkbn.com/2014/01/23/former-warren-mayor-seeks-state-post/ |title=Former Warren mayor seeks state post |work=WKBN |location=Youngstown |date=2014-01-23 |accessdate=2014-12-06 }}</ref> He would win a three way primary race with 60% of the vote for the Democratic nomination.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vindy.com/news/2014/may/07/trumbull-voters-tap-two-obriens-for-seat/ |title=Mike O\u2019Brien gets primary nod for 64th House |work=Vindicator |location=Youngstown |date=2014-05-07 |accessdate=2014-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110190626/http://www.vindy.com/news/2014/may/07/trumbull-voters-tap-two-obriens-for-seat/ |archive-date=2019-01-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He faced former Republican state Representative [[Randy Law]] in the general election, in what became a very tight race. He defeated Law 49%-44% to take the seat.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://wytv.com/2014/11/04/obrien-to-represent-ohios-64th-district-2/ |title=O\u2019Brien to represent Ohio\u2019s 64th district |work=WYTV |location=Youngstown |date=2014-11-04 |accessdate=2014-12-06 }}</ref> His district includes half of [[Trumbull County, Ohio|Trumbull County]] and the southern portion of [[Ashtabula County, Ohio|Ashtabula County]].\n\nIn 2005, Mayor Michael J. O'Brien was fined by the Ohio Ethics Committee for mishandling campaign contributions.\n\n\"According to a complaint filed in July by Victor V. Vigluicci, special prosecutor in Trumbull County, O'Brien from 2000 to 2003 received $2,035 in campaign contributions that were deposited into the joint personal checking account with his wife, or the personal savings of son Dominic and Louise O'Brien.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vindy.com/news/2005/sep/02/campaign-finance-obrien-fined-in-elections/?print|title=CAMPAIGN FINANCE O'Brien fined in elections violation|website=www.vindy.com|access-date=2016-09-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009. Mayor O'Brien proposed laying off 20 police officers and 11 firefighters in order to balance the Warren City budget.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wfmj.com/story/9368716/mayor-announces-warren-city-layoffs|title=Mayor Announces Warren City Layoffs|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref> This was after he hired 48 new city employees during his first term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tribtoday.com/page/content.detail/id/523523/Hiring-in-city-not-a-logical-practice.html?nav=5007|title=Hiring in city not a logical practice - TribToday.com - News, Sports, Jobs, Community Information -  Tribune Chronicle - Warren, OH|website=www.tribtoday.com|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref>\n\n\"As late as April 2008, when financial devastation was as clear as a bell, O'Brien hired four police officers, including Councilwoman Susan Hartman's son. A few months later they received their layoff notices.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tribtoday.com/page/content.detail/id/523523/Hiring-in-city-not-a-logical-practice.html?nav=5007|title=Hiring in city not a logical practice - TribToday.com - News, Sports, Jobs, Community Information -  Tribune Chronicle - Warren, OH|website=www.tribtoday.com|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Links==\n*[https://www.facebook.com/electmichaelobrien campaign Facebook page]\n*[http://www.electmichaelobrien.com/ campaign site]\n{{Members of the Ohio House of Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:OBrien, Michael}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Ohio Democrats]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Warren, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Youngstown State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio city council members]]\n[[Category:County commissioners in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Ohio]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-OHRepresentative-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: three way \u2192 three-way", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_O%27Brien_(Ohio_politician)"}
