{"title_page": "Sam Hall (diver)", "text_new": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = \n| image          =Sam Hall 1960.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =Hall in 1960\n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = \n| nationality    = \n| residence      = \n| birth_date     = March 10, 1937 \n| birth_place    = [[Dayton, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date     = August 11, 2014 (aged 77)\n| death_place    = [[Florida]], U.S.\n| height         = 175 cm<ref name=sr>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ha/sam-hall-1.html Sam Hall]. sports-reference.com</ref>\n| weight         = 70 kg\n| country        = \n| sport          = Diving\n| event = \n| club           = WBNS Swim Club \n| alma_mater = \n| retired        = \n| olympics       = \n| highestranking = \n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Country | the {{USA}} }}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver| [[1960 Summer Olympics|1960 Rome]] | [[Diving at the 1960 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 3 metre springboard|Springboard]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver| [[Diving at the 1959 Pan American Games|1959 Chicago]] | Springboard}} \n}}\n'''Samuel \"Sam\" Wesley Hall''' (March 10, 1937 &ndash; August 11, 2014) was an [[United States|American]] [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] [[silver medal]]ist diver and member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]]. He was born in [[Dayton, Ohio]], where his father [[Dave Hall (mayor of Dayton, Ohio)|Dave]] was [[List of mayors of Dayton, Ohio|mayor]]. His brother was Ambassador [[Tony P. Hall]]. During his last years he resided in [[Florida]], working in real estate.\n\n==Olympics 1960==\nSam Hall's extraordinary athletic career began at [[Kettering, Ohio|Kettering]]-[[Fairmont High School (Ohio)|Fairmont High School]]; he was a two-time letterwinner in track and field. During his senior season (1955), Sam established a school record in the pole vault (11-3). His record setting performance came at the Miami Valley League Championships, helping propel Fairmont to the MVL team title; the first in school history. While attending Fairmont, Sam also competed in springboard diving; a sport he pursued at the club level.<ref name=sr/>\n \nIn the fall of 1955, Hall enrolled at the Ohio State University; while attending O.S.U, Sam lettered in four sports \u2013 gymnastics, soccer, track and diving. As a trackman, Hall competed in the pole vault and javelin; his success in those events led to a crossroads: should he pursue a berth on the US Olympic track and field team, or concentrate on diving. Ultimately, Sam chose diving; he was rewarded with international acclaim.<ref name=sr/>\n\nDuring 1959\u20131960, Sam won two Big-Ten Conference championships, three NCAA championships, and three U.S. Amateur Athletic Union titles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.org/library/records/swimming/2005/2005_m_swimming_champ_record.pdf |title=Swimming and Diving |access-date=2007-07-22 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704223147/http://www.ncaa.org/library/records/swimming/2005/2005_m_swimming_champ_record.pdf |archive-date=2007-07-04 |publisher=ncaa.org}}</ref> The pinnacle of Sam Hall's diving career was his silver medal performance at both the 1959 Pan American Games and [[1960 Summer Olympics]] in Rome, Italy.<ref>[http://www.databaseolympics.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=HALLSAM01 Sam Hall Olympic medals and stats] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070216145626/http://www.databaseolympics.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=HALLSAM01 |date=2007-02-16 }}</ref>\n\nAfter the 1960 Olympics Hall served with the U.S. Air Force and competed in athletics for them, eventually retiring due to a knee injury.<ref name=sr/>\n\n==Ohio politics==\nIn 1965, Hall served in the [[Ohio House of Representatives]].<ref>Hershey, William (December 17, 1986) \"Sam Hall: Flag-waver or just an egomaniac?\". ''The Lakeland Ledger'' (Lakeland, Florida), pp. 1A, 11A</ref><ref>[http://iacsp.s2institute.com/instructor.php?instid=hall Sam Hall]. IACSP</ref>\n\n==Counterterrorist==\nHall later worked as an unpaid \"volunteer counterterrorist,\" as Hall described himself,<ref>Smolowe, Jill (December 29, 1986) [http://time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,963128-2,00.html Nicaragua an Ordeal Ends, Another Begins]. ''Time''.</ref> going to [[Central America]] to fight on the side of [[anti-communism|anti-communist]] forces as an advisor to the [[Nicaragua]]n [[Contras]]. He reentered the national spotlight again in late 1986 when he was captured by [[Sandinista National Liberation Front]] forces, which announced the capture of a \"spy\". Hall was freed after less than two months.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DEFD6113DF932A35751C0A961948260 | work=The New York Times | title=HEADLINERS; Out of Nicaragua | date=February 1, 1987 | accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHall died in Florida on August 11, 2014, aged 77.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whio.com/news/news/local/dayton-native-olympian-sam-hall-has-died/ng2S8/ |title=Dayton native, Olympian Sam Hall has died |date=2014-08-13|author=Stewart, Chris |publisher=WHIO |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814021900/http://www.whio.com/news/news/local/dayton-native-olympian-sam-hall-has-died/ng2S8/ |archive-date=2014-08-14 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons category|Sam Hall (diver)}}\n*{{cite book |last=Hall |first=Sam |authorlink= |author2=Larry Hussman |author3=Felicia Lewis |others= |title=Counter-Terrorist |year=1987 |month= |edition= |publisher=D. I. Fine |location=New York |isbn=978-1-55611-049-8 |oclc=16873424 |doi= |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/counterterrorist00hall }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, Sam}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:American athlete-politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:American mercenaries]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Dayton, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes men's divers]]\n[[Category:Olympic divers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Divers at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for the United States in diving]]\n[[Category:American male divers]]\n[[Category:American people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:People of the Nicaraguan Revolution]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in diving]]\n[[Category:Divers at the 1959 Pan American Games]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-OHRepresentative-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = \n| image          =Sam Hall 1960.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =Hall in 1960\n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = \n| nationality    = \n| residence      = \n| birth_date     = March 10, 1937 \n| birth_place    = [[Dayton, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date     = August 11, 2014 (aged 77)\n| death_place    = [[Florida]], U.S.\n| height         = 175 cm<ref name=sr>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ha/sam-hall-1.html Sam Hall]. sports-reference.com</ref>\n| weight         = 70 kg\n| country        = \n| sport          = Diving\n| event = \n| club           = WBNS Swim Club \n| alma_mater = \n| retired        = \n| olympics       = \n| highestranking = \n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Country | the {{USA}} }}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver| [[1960 Summer Olympics|1960 Rome]] | [[Diving at the 1960 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 3 metre springboard|Springboard]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver| [[Diving at the 1959 Pan American Games|1959 Chicago]] | Springboard}} \n}}\n'''Samuel \"Sam\" Wesley Hall''' (March 10, 1937 &ndash; August 11, 2014) was an [[United States|American]] [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] [[silver medal]]ist diver and member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]]. He was born in [[Dayton, Ohio]], where his father [[Dave Hall (mayor of Dayton, Ohio)|Dave]] was [[List of mayors of Dayton, Ohio|mayor]]. His brother was Ambassador [[Tony P. Hall]]. During his last years he resided in [[Florida]], working in real estate.\n\n==Olympics 1960==\nSam Hall's extraordinary athletic career began at [[Kettering, Ohio|Kettering]]-[[Fairmont High School (Ohio)|Fairmont High School]]; he was a two-time letterwinner in track and field. During his senior season (1955), Sam established a school record in the pole vault (11-3). His record setting performance came at the Miami Valley League Championships, helping propel Fairmont to the MVL team title; the first in school history. While attending Fairmont, Sam also competed in springboard diving; a sport he pursued at the club level.<ref name=sr/>\n \nIn the fall of 1955, Hall enrolled at the Ohio State University; while attending O.S.U, Sam lettered in four sports \u2013 gymnastics, soccer, track and diving. As a trackman, Hall competed in the pole vault and javelin; his success in those events led to a crossroads: should he pursue a berth on the US Olympic track and field team, or concentrate on diving. Ultimately, Sam chose diving; he was rewarded with international acclaim.<ref name=sr/>\n\nDuring 1959-1960, Sam won two Big-Ten Conference championships, three NCAA championships, and three U.S. Amateur Athletic Union titles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.org/library/records/swimming/2005/2005_m_swimming_champ_record.pdf |title=Swimming and Diving |access-date=2007-07-22 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704223147/http://www.ncaa.org/library/records/swimming/2005/2005_m_swimming_champ_record.pdf |archive-date=2007-07-04 |publisher=ncaa.org}}</ref> The pinnacle of Sam Hall's diving career was his silver medal performance at both the 1959 Pan American Games and [[1960 Summer Olympics]] in Rome, Italy.<ref>[http://www.databaseolympics.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=HALLSAM01 Sam Hall Olympic medals and stats] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070216145626/http://www.databaseolympics.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=HALLSAM01 |date=2007-02-16 }}</ref>\n\nAfter the 1960 Olympics Hall served with the U.S. Air Force and competed in athletics for them, eventually retiring due to a knee injury.<ref name=sr/>\n\n==Ohio politics==\nIn 1965, Hall served in the [[Ohio House of Representatives]].<ref>Hershey, William (December 17, 1986) \"Sam Hall: Flag-waver or just an egomaniac?\". ''The Lakeland Ledger'' (Lakeland, Florida), pp. 1A, 11A</ref><ref>[http://iacsp.s2institute.com/instructor.php?instid=hall Sam Hall]. IACSP</ref>\n\n==Counterterrorist==\nHall later worked as an unpaid \"volunteer counterterrorist,\" as Hall described himself,<ref>Smolowe, Jill (December 29, 1986) [http://time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,963128-2,00.html Nicaragua an Ordeal Ends, Another Begins]. ''Time''.</ref> going to [[Central America]] to fight on the side of [[anti-communism|anti-communist]] forces as an advisor to the [[Nicaragua]]n [[Contras]]. He reentered the national spotlight again in late 1986 when he was captured by [[Sandinista National Liberation Front]] forces, which announced the capture of a \"spy\". Hall was freed after less than two months.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DEFD6113DF932A35751C0A961948260 | work=The New York Times | title=HEADLINERS; Out of Nicaragua | date=February 1, 1987 | accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHall died in Florida on August 11, 2014, aged 77.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whio.com/news/news/local/dayton-native-olympian-sam-hall-has-died/ng2S8/ |title=Dayton native, Olympian Sam Hall has died |date=2014-08-13|author=Stewart, Chris |publisher=WHIO |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814021900/http://www.whio.com/news/news/local/dayton-native-olympian-sam-hall-has-died/ng2S8/ |archive-date=2014-08-14 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons category|Sam Hall (diver)}}\n*{{cite book |last=Hall |first=Sam |authorlink= |author2=Larry Hussman |author3=Felicia Lewis |others= |title=Counter-Terrorist |year=1987 |month= |edition= |publisher=D. I. Fine |location=New York |isbn=978-1-55611-049-8 |oclc=16873424 |doi= |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/counterterrorist00hall }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, Sam}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:American athlete-politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:American mercenaries]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Dayton, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes men's divers]]\n[[Category:Olympic divers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Divers at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for the United States in diving]]\n[[Category:American male divers]]\n[[Category:American people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:People of the Nicaraguan Revolution]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in diving]]\n[[Category:Divers at the 1959 Pan American Games]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-OHRepresentative-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOlympics 1960:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1959-1960 \u2192 1959\u20131960", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sam_Hall_(diver)"}
{"title_page": "Marc Guthrie", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Marc Guthrie\n| image        = \n| order1       = Member of the<br>[[Ohio House of Representatives]]<br>from the 71st district\n| term1  = January 3, 1983-December 31, 1994\n| term_end1    = \n| predecessor1 = [[Eugene Branstool]]\n| successor1   = [[Jay Hottinger]]\n<!--Personal data-->\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1952|02|08}}\n| birth_place  = \n| party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| residence    = [[Newark, Ohio]]\n}}\n\n'''Marc Guthrie''' (born February 8, 1952) is a [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] politician who formerly served in the [[Ohio General Assembly]]. Guthrie began his political career as a member of the [[Heath, Ohio]] City Council, and went on to serve six years as a [[Licking County, Ohio]] Commissioner. When [[Eugene Branstool]] opted to give up his seat in [[Ohio House of Representatives]] to run for the [[Ohio Senate]], Guthrie entered the race to succeed him. He was successful, and was sworn into office on January 3, 1983. He won reelection in 1984, 1986, and 1988.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.access-board.gov/news/951-marc-d-guthrie-appointed-to-the-u-s-access-board |title=Marc D. Guthrie Appointed to the U.S. Access Board |language= |date=2012-11-23 |accessdate=2014-12-31 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, there was much speculation that Congress, however he opted to again run for his seat in the Statehouse. Soon after, he became assistant majority whip in the House. He won a sixth term in 1992.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wclt.com/news/wclt/wclt6345.html |title=http://www.wclt.com/news/wclt/wclt6345.html |work=WCLT |location=Newark |date=2003-02-12 |accessdate=2014-12-31 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Guthrie announced that he would forgo a seventh term in the House to run for the [[Ohio Senate]], opting to take on newly appointed Senator [[Nancy Dix]]. With the year being overwhelmingly Republican, Guthrie lost for the first time, ending his career as a state legislator after twelve years.\n\nGuthrie opted to return to politics in 2000, by running for Congress against Congressman [[Bob Ney]]. With a colorful campaign including support from [[Jerry Springer]], Guthrie provided Ney with a contested race. In the end, Ney received 64% of the vote to Guthrie's 36%. Following his Congressional defeat, Guthrie returned to Newark where he opted to run for Newark City Council. He ended up serving on the council from 2003\u20132009, and again from 2011 to 2015.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Links==\n*[http://www.newarkohio.net/government/city-council/council-members City of Newark - Council Members]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guthrie, Marc}}\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Ohio Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Heath, Ohio]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Newark, Ohio]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-OHRepresentative-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Marc Guthrie\n| image        = \n| order1       = Member of the<br>[[Ohio House of Representatives]]<br>from the 71st district\n| term1  = January 3, 1983-December 31, 1994\n| term_end1    = \n| predecessor1 = [[Eugene Branstool]]\n| successor1   = [[Jay Hottinger]]\n<!--Personal data-->\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1952|02|08}}\n| birth_place  = \n| party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| residence    = [[Newark, Ohio]]\n}}\n\n'''Marc Guthrie''' (born February 8, 1952) is a [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] politician who formerly served in the [[Ohio General Assembly]]. Guthrie began his political career as a member of the [[Heath, Ohio]] City Council, and went on to serve six years as a [[Licking County, Ohio]] Commissioner. When [[Eugene Branstool]] opted to give up his seat in [[Ohio House of Representatives]] to run for the [[Ohio Senate]], Guthrie entered the race to succeed him. He was successful, and was sworn into office on January 3, 1983. He won reelection in 1984, 1986, and 1988.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.access-board.gov/news/951-marc-d-guthrie-appointed-to-the-u-s-access-board |title=Marc D. Guthrie Appointed to the U.S. Access Board |language= |date=2012-11-23 |accessdate=2014-12-31 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, there was much speculation that Congress, however he opted to again run for his seat in the Statehouse. Soon after, he became assistant majority whip in the House. He won a sixth term in 1992.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wclt.com/news/wclt/wclt6345.html |title=http://www.wclt.com/news/wclt/wclt6345.html |work=WCLT |location=Newark |date=2003-02-12 |accessdate=2014-12-31 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Guthrie announced that he would forgo a seventh term in the House to run for the [[Ohio Senate]], opting to take on newly appointed Senator [[Nancy Dix]]. With the year being overwhelmingly Republican, Guthrie lost for the first time, ending his career as a state legislator after twelve years.\n\nGuthrie opted to return to politics in 2000, by running for Congress against Congressman [[Bob Ney]]. With a colorful campaign including support from [[Jerry Springer]], Guthrie provided Ney with a contested race. In the end, Ney received 64% of the vote to Guthrie's 36%. Following his Congressional defeat, Guthrie returned to Newark where he opted to run for Newark City Council. He ended up serving on the council from 2003-2009, and again from 2011 to 2015.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Links==\n*[http://www.newarkohio.net/government/city-council/council-members City of Newark - Council Members]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guthrie, Marc}}\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Ohio Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Heath, Ohio]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Newark, Ohio]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-OHRepresentative-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2003-2009 \u2192 2003\u20132009", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marc_Guthrie"}
{"title_page": "Larry L. Flowers", "text_new": "{{Infobox State Representative\n|image = \n|imagesize = 150px\n| name=Larry L. Flowers\n|image name=\n|state_house=Ohio\n|state=Ohio\n|district=19th\n|term=January 3, 2001-December 31, 2008\n|preceded=[[Jo Ann Davidson]]\n|succeeded=[[Marian Harris]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1952|05|06}}\n|birth_place=[[Newark, Ohio]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|spouse=Patty\n|profession=[[fire chief]]\n|religion=[[Methodist]]\n|party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n}}\n\n'''Larry L. Flowers''' is a former [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]], representing the 19th District from 2001\u20132008.  He currently is serving as the fire marshal for the state of [[Ohio]].\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080315210210/http://www.house.state.oh.us/jsps/MemberDetails.jsp?DISTRICT=19 The Ohio Senate - Larry L. Flowers] '''official OH House website'''\n*[http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=45549 Project Vote Smart - Representative Larry L. Flowers (OH)] profile\n*''Follow the Money'' - Larry L. Flowers\n**[http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?si=200635&c=422724 2006] [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?si=200435&c=399623 2004] [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?si=200235&c=22613 2002] [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?si=200035&c=374276 2000] campaign contributions\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flowers, Larry L.}}\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Newark, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Ohio Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-OHRepresentative-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox State Representative\n|image = \n|imagesize = 150px\n| name=Larry L. Flowers\n|image name=\n|state_house=Ohio\n|state=Ohio\n|district=19th\n|term=January 3, 2001-December 31, 2008\n|preceded=[[Jo Ann Davidson]]\n|succeeded=[[Marian Harris]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1952|05|06}}\n|birth_place=[[Newark, Ohio]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|spouse=Patty\n|profession=[[fire chief]]\n|religion=[[Methodist]]\n|party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n}}\n\n'''Larry L. Flowers''' is a former [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]], representing the 19th District from 2001-2008.  He currently is serving as the fire marshal for the state of [[Ohio]].\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080315210210/http://www.house.state.oh.us/jsps/MemberDetails.jsp?DISTRICT=19 The Ohio Senate - Larry L. Flowers] '''official OH House website'''\n*[http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=45549 Project Vote Smart - Representative Larry L. Flowers (OH)] profile\n*''Follow the Money'' - Larry L. Flowers\n**[http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?si=200635&c=422724 2006] [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?si=200435&c=399623 2004] [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?si=200235&c=22613 2002] [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?si=200035&c=374276 2000] campaign contributions\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flowers, Larry L.}}\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Newark, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Ohio Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-OHRepresentative-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2001-2008 \u2192 2001\u20132008", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Larry_L._Flowers"}
{"title_page": "B. F. Brisac", "text_new": "{{COI|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = B. F. Brisac\n| birth_name         = Belnore Felix Brisac\n| image              = Belnore_Felix_Brisac_c1908.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = B. F. Brisac (about 1908)\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date |1858|9|15|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1940|1|6|1858|9|15|mf=y}}\n| death_place        = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n| resting place      = Ashes interred in Mt. Olivet Memorial Park Columbarium, [[Colma, California]], U.S.\n| alma mater         = [[Santa Clara University|Santa Clara College]]\n| occupation         = Insurance broker, business executive\n| years_active       = 1877\u20131940\n| spouse(s)          = {{marriage|Alice Hain|1878|1924|end=died}}<br>{{marriage|Lena A. Shell<br>|1930}}\n| children           = 2, including [[Virginia Brissac]]\n| family             = [[Ardel Wray]] (granddaughter)<br> [[Mary Shaw (actress)|Mary Shaw]] (sister-in-law)\n}}\n\n'''B. F. Brisac''' (September 15, 1858 \u2013 January 6, 1940) was an American business executive and humanitarian known for his work with the San Francisco Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals and other humane organizations in the early 1900s.\n\n==Early life and career==\nBrisac was born Belnore Felix Brisac in San Francisco, CA in 1858, the son of Felix and Virginia (Grain) Brisac. His father was a French expatriate in the line of the Dukes of Brissac.{{refn|name=\"FB\"|group=lower-alpha|Brisac's father, Felix (1811\u20131882) is believed to have been a descendant of Timol\u00e9on de Coss\u00e9-Brissac, 9th [[Dukes of Brissac|Duke of Brissac]].  The family [[Ch\u00e2teau de Brissac|castle]] had been ransacked in the [[French Revolution]] and lay in ruins for half a century until a restoration project<ref>{{cite web |title=The Castle of Brissac |url=http://worldtourisminfo.com/france/2432-The-castle-of-Brissac-photo-description-Chateau-de-Brissac.html |website=World Tourism Info |accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref> was begun by the surviving heirs of Roda de Brissac in 1844, the same year that Felix - a child of the [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] - left France. Sometime after he left, Felix dropped an 's' from the spelling of his last name (he may have changed his first name as well), and became a naturalized American citizen. When Timol\u00e9on died in 1848, the ducal title went unclaimed for the next thirty-five years. In 1883, the year after Felix died, the French aristocrat and author [[Fran\u00e7ois de Coss\u00e9 Brissac, 11th Duke of Brissac|Fran\u00e7ois de Coss\u00e9 Brissac]] assumed the title of 11th Duke of Brissac, and both the castle and the title have remained in his family ever since. In historical accounts of this lineage, Felix and his sons Camille, Norline, and Belnore are referred to only as 'successive descendants in the male line' of Timol\u00e9on de Coss\u00e9-Brissac.}}  His mother was the daughter of French-American painter and [[scenographer]] Fredrick Grain.{{refn|name=\"Grain\"|group=lower-alpha|Brisac's grandfather, Frederick Grain (1790\u20131864), was an orphaned infant son of French colonials killed in the overthrow of French rule during the [[Haitian Revolution]] of 1791.  He was rescued by friends of his parents who managed to escape and take him with them to New York, where he grew up and, ultimately, became a painter.<ref name=\"Estate\">Virginia Brissac family history and estate records (courtesy of Stefani Warren).</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Frederick Grain |url=https://americanart.si.edu/artist/frederick-grain-6425 |website=Smithsonian American Art Museum |accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>  His brother [[Peter Grain (artist)|Peter Grain]] was also a painter, as were Peter's sons, and the [[Peter Grain (artist)#Family of artists|Grain family]] was described by one critic as being among the best theatre scenic artists of their day.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lacy |first1=Robin-Thurlow |title=A Biographical Dictionary of Scenographers |date=1990 |publisher=Greenwood Press. |pages=260\u2013262}}</ref>}}  He had two brothers, Camille (1851\u20131855) and Norline (1856\u20131903).{{refn|name=\"NB\"|group=lower-alpha|As Felix Brisac's eldest son after Camille (who died in childhood), Brisac's brother Norline could have assumed his inherited ducal title after his father died in 1882, but he had no interest in it.  According to estate archivists at The Lilly Library (Indiana University, Bloomington): \"Norline Frederick Brisac was a California born, globe-trotting, would-be actor and bonvivant whose irresponsible lifestyle earned the disapproval of his wealthy father, who eventually refused to continue to fund his son's 'educational expenses'.  He was briefly married to the actress [[Mary Shaw (actress)|Mary Shaw]].\"<ref name=\"LILLYLIB\">{{cite web |title=Norline Frederick Brisac (LMC 2687), Biographical Note (based on letters and other memorabilia contained in the estate of Mary Shaw) |url=http://webapp1.dlib.indiana.edu/findingaids/view?doc.view=entire_text&docId=InU-Li-VAD6135 |website=Online Archives at Indiana University |publisher=The Lilly Library (Indiana University, Bloomington) |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nKnown professionally as B. F. Brisac, Belnore began his career working for Murphy Grant & Company (importers and jobbers of dry goods) in San Francisco in 1877. When his father died in 1882, he went to work as an insurance soliciter with The Liverpool & London & Globe Insurance Company (LLG), filling the position his father had held there. He later became a broker and continued his affiliation with LLG for the next thirty years.{{refn|name=\"EstateLetters\"|Letter of reference (Murphy Grant & Company, January 20, 1882) and Offer letter (Resident Secretary of Liverpool & London & Globe Insurance Company, January 20, 1882). In Virginia Brissac estate records.<ref name=\"Estate\" />}}\n\nBrisac also invested time and money in Bay area development ventures. A proponent of the [[Olympic Games|modern Olympic Movement]], he joined and later became a Director of the [[Olympic Club]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Programme, the Olympic Club Fair, Revival Ancient Graeco-Roman Games [April 17th to 22nd, 1893] |url=https://www.olyclub.com/history/ |website=Olyclub.com |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref> He owned stock in the Olympic Salt Water Company (1894) and was Vice President and General Manager of the Boulder Creek Electric Light and Water Company which he helped found in 1903.<ref>{{cite book |title=Report of the Railroad Commission |date=1920 |publisher=California State Printing Office |location=Sacramento, CA |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZADWAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA313&dq=B.F.+Brisac&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjS6Lb2jYffAhVjlVQKHdLDBYUQ6AEISTAG#v=onepage&q=B.F.%20Brisac&f=false |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Work on insurance reforms===\n[[File:B. F. Brisac - post SF Earthquake and Fire 1906.jpg|thumb|B. F. Brisac (left) with others working in the basement of the damaged offices of Liverpool & London & Globe Insurance company after the San Francisco Earthquake and Fire in 1906.]]\nFollowing the [[1906 San Francisco earthquake|San Francisco earthquake and fire in 1906]], many wealthy families abandoned the city, some never to return; Brisac chose to stay. Working from the basement of their damaged office building, he and others at LLG began processing insurance claims within days of the fire being put out. The [[Eugene Schmitz|Mayor of San Francisco]] had declared martial law and issued a shoot-to-kill order for looters.<ref>{{cite web |title=Martial Law Declared in San Francisco |url=https://archives.nbclearn.com/portal/site/k-12/flatview?cuecard=33119 |website=NBC Learn |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Proclamation by the Mayor |url=http://www.sfmuseum.org/1906.2/killproc.html |website=Virtual Museum of the City of San Francisco |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref> To speed the payouts that would allow families to keep their property, Brisac secured a pass from the Mayor and for weeks traversed San Francisco with a money belt and a pistol for self-protection while paying off claims.<ref name=\"Estate\" /><ref>\"Gifts Received by the Society: December 1, 1939, through February 29, 1940.\" California Historical Society Quarterly 19, no. 1 (1940): 84. https://www.jstor.org/stable/25160864.</ref>\n\nThe massive earthquake damage, and the rampant [[1906 San Francisco earthquake#Fires|fraud following the fire]] combined to force many insurance companies to go bankrupt or abandon policy holders,<ref>{{cite web |title=Insurance Claims |url=http://bancroft.berkeley.edu/collections/earthquakeandfire/exhibit/room05_item02.html |website=The Bancroft Library presents The 1906 San Francisco Earthquake and Fire (Online Exhibit) |publisher=University of California, Berkeley |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wells |first1=Britton |title=Lloyd\u2019s sees 1906 San Francisco earthquake as a turning point |url=https://www.insurancejournal.com/magazines/mag-features/2006/05/08/69889.htm |website=Insurance Journal |publisher=Wells Media Group Inc. |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref> but Liverpool & London & Globe survived and Brisac became an advocate for insurance reforms, working as a member and later Chairman of the Board of Governors of the Insurance Broker's Exchange of San Francisco.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Insurance Men Planning Central Conference Body |journal=San Francisco Business |date=July 8, 1921 |volume=3 |page=31 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=53C4AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA31&dq=B.F.+Brisac&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiihIHOkoffAhUR2FQKHcMQA0IQ6AEIRDAF#v=onepage&q=Insurance%20Conference%20Committee%2C%20B.F.%20Brisac&f=false|accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Brokers Endorse Stock Insurance |journal=The Eastern Underwriter |date=August 25, 1922 |page=18 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f0qzkazf8fIC&pg=RA8-PA19&dq=B.F.+Brisac&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiy2JShmIffAhUTK3wKHf_gCVg4HhDoAQhHMAY#v=onepage&q=B.F.%20Brisac&f=true}}</ref>\n\nBrisac was involved in San Francisco's reconstruction efforts for over a decade. In 1914, he chaired the Insurance Broker's Committee of the World's Insurance Congress,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Broker's Committee |journal=The Adjuster|date=July 1914 |volume=49|issue=1|page=67 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m-U7AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA148&dq=Insurance+Broker%E2%80%99s+Committee,+World+Insurance+Congress,+B.+F.+Brisac&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjFiczEwLHfAhUHiFQKHbz4Ap0Q6AEINDAC#v=onepage&q=Insurance%20Broker%E2%80%99s%20Committee%2C%20World%20Insurance%20Congress%2C%20B.%20F.%20Brisac&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Items of Insurance News |journal=The Economic World |date=August 1915 |volume=94|page=148 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m-U7AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA148&dq=Insurance+Broker%E2%80%99s+Committee,+World+Insurance+Congress,+B.+F.+Brisac&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjFiczEwLHfAhUHiFQKHbz4Ap0Q6AEINDAC#v=onepage&q=Insurance%20Broker%E2%80%99s%20Committee%2C%20World%20Insurance%20Congress%2C%20B.%20F.%20Brisac&f=false}}</ref> and invested in the 1914 [[Panama\u2013Pacific International Exposition]],<ref name=\"Estate\" /> and he continued to contribute to disaster relief efforts such as the [[1918 San Jacinto earthquake|1918 San Jacinto Earthquake]] Fund.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Contributors to the Hemet and San Jacinto Earthquake Fund |journal=San Francisco Chamber of Commerce Activities |date=May 23, 1918 |volume=5 |issue= 21 |page=158 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P_c4AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA158&dq=Brisac+and+Albert+Bender&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwim8tr-8KDfAhWIw1QKHagJDMEQ6AEIRTAF#v=onepage&q=Brisac%20and%20Albert%20Bender&f=false}}</ref>\n\nAlong with other survivors, Brisac struggled to come to terms with the death and destruction caused by the earthquake, and he found consolation in the teachings of the new [[Christian Science]]. In 1908, he introduced Christian Science lecturer F. H. Leonard to a crowd of 4000 in the Dreamland Rink auditorium in San Francisco. Acknowledging the large turnout, Brisac proposed that the question on everyone's mind was \u201cWhat is there in it?\u201d and suggested that it offered what humanity was missing \u2013 \u201c...reconciliation with god.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |title=Lecturer Explains Christian Science |publisher=The San Francisco Call |date=December 7, 1908|volume=105(7)|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=SFC19081207.2.67&srpos=47&dliv=none&e=-------en--20--41--txt-txIN-Brisac-------1}}</ref> In 1913, he was elected First Reader in the newly built San Francisco First Church of Christ, Scientist.<ref>{{cite news |title=Christian Scientists Form New Church |publisher=The San Francisco Call |date=November 15, 1913|volume=114(158)|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=SFC19131115.2.40&srpos=20&dliv=none&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-Brisac-------1}}</ref>\n\n===Work with humane organizations===\nBrisac grew up in the waning days of the [[California Gold Rush]] and witnessed the routine abuse of dray horses and mules on San Francisco streets, and he had known about the work of the [[San Francisco SPCA|Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals]] since its founding in 1868. But his involvement with the group didn't begin until, in the aftermath of the earthquake in 1906, he assisted in the rescue of trapped and injured animals and helped build water troughs for the horses used in rescue and reconstruction. He joined the Society in 1907 and was active for the rest of his life, as a member (1907\u20131916), Trustee (1916\u20131930) and President (1930\u20131940). At the time of his death, he was also First Vice-President, formerly President of the State Humane Association of California and Director of the [[American Humane|American Humane Association]] active in American [[Red Star Rescue]] and Animal Relief.<ref name=\"Memorial\">{{cite journal |title=In Memorium: B. F. Brisac |journal=Our Animals (publication of the San Francisco Society of the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals) |date=January 1940 |volume=33 |issue=10}}</ref>\n\n==Family life and later years==\n[[File:AW-BFB-VB c1920.jpg|thumb|B. F. Brisac with daughter [[Virginia Brissac]] (right) and granddaughter [[Ardel Wray]] (left), around 1922.]]\nBrisac married Alice M. Hain in 1878 and they had two children - [[Virginia Brissac|Virginia]], born in 1883, and Belnore Brisac, Jr. born in 1888.\n\nWhen Virginia was nineteen, Brisac and his wife were persuaded by friend and local theatre impresario Reginald Travers to allow her to act professionally.<ref name=\"Clayton\">{{cite journal |last1=Clayton |first1=Merle |title=The Coast Defender: Virginia Brissac |journal=The San Diego Magazine |issue=January 1971 |pages=90\u2013108}}</ref>  She quickly became a headliner on the West Coast Stock theatre circuit and, in April 1906, married an actor she met while on tour in Los Angeles, California. When the marriage failed in 1911,<ref name=\"divorce\">\"Virginia Brissac Granted Divorce\". ''The San Francisco Call'', May 7, 1912, p. 1</ref> Brisac made a home for Virginia's four-year-old daughter, [[Ardel Wray|Ardel]], who lived with them for over ten years before finally rejoining her mother in 1922. Brisac continued to be a surrogate father and mentor to his granddaughter until his death in 1940.{{refn|name=\"Theatre\"|group=lower-alpha|Theatre ran in Brisac's family. As a young girl growing up in Texas, his wife Alice had been interested in acting and passed that interest on to her children.  His brother, Norline - a \"would-be actor\" and sometime stage manager for [[Sarah Bernhardt]]<ref name=\"LILLYLIB\" /> - seeded his niece's interest with autographed photo postcards of famous actors.  Daughter Virginia went on to become the professional stage and screen actress [[Virginia Brissac]] (adopting the original French spelling of the family name for her stage name).  Belnore Brisac, Jr. sang and was involved in occasional amateur theatricals throughout his life, and Virginia's daughter became the Hollywood screenwriter and story editor, [[Ardel Wray]], known for the screenplays for ''[[I Walked with a Zombie]]'', ''[[The Leopard Man]]'' and ''[[Isle of the Dead (film)|Isle of the Dead]]''.  Although supportive, there is no evidence that B. F. Brisac himself had any interest in it.<ref name=\"Estate\" />}}\n\nAlice Brisac died in 1924 after a long illness. B. F. remarried in 1930, and he and his second wife continued living in San Francisco until his death ten years later.\n\n==Death and tribute==\n\nUpon his death on January 6, 1940, the Board of Trustees of The San Francisco Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals paid tribute to Brisac in a resolution which read in part: \u201cHis was a long, full and beneficent life. Kindness for his fellow men and a deep sense of consideration and responsibility for the welfare of helpless creatures were primary precepts upon which he based his conduct and living. As a humanitarian his loss will be felt throughout the entire country.\u201d<ref name=\"Memorial\"/>\n\nHis ashes were interred in the Brisac family niche, along with those of his wife and others in his family, in the Columbarium at the Mt. Olivet Memorial Park in Colma, California outside of San Francisco.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brisac, B.F.}}\n[[Category:People from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Animal welfare and rights in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = B. F. Brisac\n| birth_name         = Belnore Felix Brisac\n| image              = Belnore_Felix_Brisac_c1908.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = B. F. Brisac (about 1908)\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date |1858|9|15|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1940|1|6|1858|9|15|mf=y}}\n| death_place        = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n| resting place      = Ashes interred in Mt. Olivet Memorial Park Columbarium, [[Colma, California]], U.S.\n| alma mater         = [[Santa Clara University|Santa Clara College]]\n| occupation         = Insurance broker, business executive\n| years_active       = 1877\u20131940\n| spouse(s)          = {{marriage|Alice Hain|1878|1924|end=died}}<br>{{marriage|Lena A. Shell<br>|1930}}\n| children           = 2, including [[Virginia Brissac]]\n| family             = [[Ardel Wray]] (granddaughter)<br> [[Mary Shaw (actress)|Mary Shaw]] (sister-in-law)\n}}\n\n'''B. F. Brisac''' (September 15, 1858 \u2013 January 6, 1940) was an American business executive and humanitarian known for his work with the San Francisco Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals and other humane organizations in the early 1900s.\n\n==Early life and career==\nBrisac was born Belnore Felix Brisac in San Francisco, CA in 1858, the son of Felix and Virginia (Grain) Brisac. His father was a French ex-patriot in the line of the Dukes of Brissac.{{refn|name=\"FB\"|group=lower-alpha|Brisac's father, Felix (1811\u20131882) is believed to have been a descendant of Timol\u00e9on de Coss\u00e9-Brissac, 9th [[Dukes of Brissac|Duke of Brissac]].  The family [[Ch\u00e2teau de Brissac|castle]] had been ransacked in the [[French Revolution]] and lay in ruins for half a century until a restoration project<ref>{{cite web |title=The Castle of Brissac |url=http://worldtourisminfo.com/france/2432-The-castle-of-Brissac-photo-description-Chateau-de-Brissac.html |website=World Tourism Info |accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref> was begun by the surviving heirs of Roda de Brissac in 1844, the same year that Felix - a child of the [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] - left France. Sometime after he left, Felix dropped an 's' from the spelling of his last name (he may have changed his first name as well), and became a naturalized American citizen. When Timol\u00e9on died in 1848, the ducal title went unclaimed for the next thirty-five years. In 1883, the year after Felix died, the French aristocrat and author [[Fran\u00e7ois de Coss\u00e9 Brissac, 11th Duke of Brissac|Fran\u00e7ois de Coss\u00e9 Brissac]] assumed the title of 11th Duke of Brissac, and both the castle and the title have remained in his family ever since. In historical accounts of this lineage, Felix and his sons Camille, Norline, and Belnore are referred to only as 'successive descendants in the male line' of Timol\u00e9on de Coss\u00e9-Brissac.}}  His mother was the daughter of French-American painter and [[scenographer]] Fredrick Grain.{{refn|name=\"Grain\"|group=lower-alpha|Brisac's grandfather, Frederick Grain (1790\u20131864), was an orphaned infant son of French colonials killed in the overthrow of French rule during the [[Haitian Revolution]] of 1791.  He was rescued by friends of his parents who managed to escape and take him with them to New York, where he grew up and, ultimately, became a painter.<ref name=\"Estate\">Virginia Brissac family history and estate records (courtesy of Stefani Warren).</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Frederick Grain |url=https://americanart.si.edu/artist/frederick-grain-6425 |website=Smithsonian American Art Museum |accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>  His brother [[Peter Grain (artist)|Peter Grain]] was also a painter, as were Peter's sons, and the [[Peter Grain (artist)#Family of artists|Grain family]] was described by one critic as being among the best theatre scenic artists of their day.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lacy |first1=Robin-Thurlow |title=A Biographical Dictionary of Scenographers |date=1990 |publisher=Greenwood Press. |pages=260\u2013262}}</ref>}}  He had two brothers, Camille (1851\u20131855) and Norline (1856\u20131903).{{refn|name=\"NB\"|group=lower-alpha|As Felix Brisac's eldest son after Camille (who died in childhood), Brisac's brother Norline could have assumed his inherited ducal title after his father died in 1882, but he had no interest in it.  According to estate archivists at The Lilly Library (Indiana University, Bloomington): \"Norline Frederick Brisac was a California born, globe-trotting, would-be actor and bonvivant whose irresponsible lifestyle earned the disapproval of his wealthy father, who eventually refused to continue to fund his son's 'educational expenses'.  He was briefly married to the actress [[Mary Shaw (actress)|Mary Shaw]].\"<ref name=\"LILLYLIB\">{{cite web |title=Norline Frederick Brisac (LMC 2687), Biographical Note (based on letters and other memorabilia contained in the estate of Mary Shaw) |url=http://webapp1.dlib.indiana.edu/findingaids/view?doc.view=entire_text&docId=InU-Li-VAD6135 |website=Online Archives at Indiana University |publisher=The Lilly Library (Indiana University, Bloomington) |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nKnown professionally as B. F. Brisac, Belnore began his career working for Murphy Grant & Company (importers and jobbers of dry goods) in San Francisco in 1877. When his father died in 1882, he went to work as an insurance soliciter with The Liverpool & London & Globe Insurance Company (LLG), filling the position his father had held there. He later became a broker and continued his affiliation with LLG for the next thirty years.{{refn|name=\"EstateLetters\"|Letter of reference (Murphy Grant & Company, January 20, 1882) and Offer letter (Resident Secretary of Liverpool & London & Globe Insurance Company, January 20, 1882). In Virginia Brissac estate records.<ref name=\"Estate\" />}}\n\nBrisac also invested time and money in Bay area development ventures. A proponent of the [[Olympic Games|modern Olympic Movement]], he joined and later became a Director of the [[Olympic Club]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Programme, the Olympic Club Fair, Revival Ancient Graeco-Roman Games [April 17th to 22nd, 1893] |url=https://www.olyclub.com/history/ |website=Olyclub.com |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref> He owned stock in the Olympic Salt Water Company (1894) and was Vice President and General Manager of the Boulder Creek Electric Light and Water Company which he helped found in 1903.<ref>{{cite book |title=Report of the Railroad Commission |date=1920 |publisher=California State Printing Office |location=Sacramento, CA |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZADWAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA313&dq=B.F.+Brisac&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjS6Lb2jYffAhVjlVQKHdLDBYUQ6AEISTAG#v=onepage&q=B.F.%20Brisac&f=false |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Work on insurance reforms===\n[[File:B. F. Brisac - post SF Earthquake and Fire 1906.jpg|thumb|B. F. Brisac (left) with others working in the basement of the damaged offices of Liverpool & London & Globe Insurance company after the San Francisco Earthquake and Fire in 1906.]]\nFollowing the [[1906 San Francisco earthquake|San Francisco earthquake and fire in 1906]], many wealthy families abandoned the city, some never to return; Brisac chose to stay. Working from the basement of their damaged office building, he and others at LLG began processing insurance claims within days of the fire being put out. The [[Eugene Schmitz|Mayor of San Francisco]] had declared martial law and issued a shoot-to-kill order for looters.<ref>{{cite web |title=Martial Law Declared in San Francisco |url=https://archives.nbclearn.com/portal/site/k-12/flatview?cuecard=33119 |website=NBC Learn |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Proclamation by the Mayor |url=http://www.sfmuseum.org/1906.2/killproc.html |website=Virtual Museum of the City of San Francisco |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref> To speed the payouts that would allow families to keep their property, Brisac secured a pass from the Mayor and for weeks traversed San Francisco with a money belt and a pistol for self-protection while paying off claims.<ref name=\"Estate\" /><ref>\"Gifts Received by the Society: December 1, 1939, through February 29, 1940.\" California Historical Society Quarterly 19, no. 1 (1940): 84. https://www.jstor.org/stable/25160864.</ref>\n\nThe massive earthquake damage, and the rampant [[1906 San Francisco earthquake#Fires|fraud following the fire]] combined to force many insurance companies to go bankrupt or abandon policy holders,<ref>{{cite web |title=Insurance Claims |url=http://bancroft.berkeley.edu/collections/earthquakeandfire/exhibit/room05_item02.html |website=The Bancroft Library presents The 1906 San Francisco Earthquake and Fire (Online Exhibit) |publisher=University of California, Berkeley |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wells |first1=Britton |title=Lloyd\u2019s sees 1906 San Francisco earthquake as a turning point |url=https://www.insurancejournal.com/magazines/mag-features/2006/05/08/69889.htm |website=Insurance Journal |publisher=Wells Media Group Inc. |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref> but Liverpool & London & Globe survived and Brisac became an advocate for insurance reforms, working as a member and later Chairman of the Board of Governors of the Insurance Broker's Exchange of San Francisco.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Insurance Men Planning Central Conference Body |journal=San Francisco Business |date=July 8, 1921 |volume=3 |page=31 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=53C4AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA31&dq=B.F.+Brisac&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiihIHOkoffAhUR2FQKHcMQA0IQ6AEIRDAF#v=onepage&q=Insurance%20Conference%20Committee%2C%20B.F.%20Brisac&f=false|accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Brokers Endorse Stock Insurance |journal=The Eastern Underwriter |date=August 25, 1922 |page=18 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f0qzkazf8fIC&pg=RA8-PA19&dq=B.F.+Brisac&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiy2JShmIffAhUTK3wKHf_gCVg4HhDoAQhHMAY#v=onepage&q=B.F.%20Brisac&f=true}}</ref>\n\nBrisac was involved in San Francisco's reconstruction efforts for over a decade. In 1914, he chaired the Insurance Broker's Committee of the World's Insurance Congress,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Broker's Committee |journal=The Adjuster|date=July 1914 |volume=49|issue=1|page=67 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m-U7AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA148&dq=Insurance+Broker%E2%80%99s+Committee,+World+Insurance+Congress,+B.+F.+Brisac&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjFiczEwLHfAhUHiFQKHbz4Ap0Q6AEINDAC#v=onepage&q=Insurance%20Broker%E2%80%99s%20Committee%2C%20World%20Insurance%20Congress%2C%20B.%20F.%20Brisac&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Items of Insurance News |journal=The Economic World |date=August 1915 |volume=94|page=148 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m-U7AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA148&dq=Insurance+Broker%E2%80%99s+Committee,+World+Insurance+Congress,+B.+F.+Brisac&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjFiczEwLHfAhUHiFQKHbz4Ap0Q6AEINDAC#v=onepage&q=Insurance%20Broker%E2%80%99s%20Committee%2C%20World%20Insurance%20Congress%2C%20B.%20F.%20Brisac&f=false}}</ref> and invested in the 1914 [[Panama\u2013Pacific International Exposition]],<ref name=\"Estate\" /> and he continued to contribute to disaster relief efforts such as the [[1918 San Jacinto earthquake|1918 San Jacinto Earthquake]] Fund.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Contributors to the Hemet and San Jacinto Earthquake Fund |journal=San Francisco Chamber of Commerce Activities |date=May 23, 1918 |volume=5 |issue= 21 |page=158 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P_c4AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA158&dq=Brisac+and+Albert+Bender&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwim8tr-8KDfAhWIw1QKHagJDMEQ6AEIRTAF#v=onepage&q=Brisac%20and%20Albert%20Bender&f=false}}</ref>\n\nAlong with other survivors, Brisac struggled to come to terms with the death and destruction caused by the earthquake, and he found consolation in the teachings of the new [[Christian Science]]. In 1908, he introduced Christian Science lecturer F. H. Leonard to a crowd of 4000 in the Dreamland Rink auditorium in San Francisco. Acknowledging the large turnout, Brisac proposed that the question on everyone's mind was \u201cWhat is there in it?\u201d and suggested that it offered what humanity was missing \u2013 \u201c...reconciliation with god.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |title=Lecturer Explains Christian Science |publisher=The San Francisco Call |date=December 7, 1908|volume=105(7)|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=SFC19081207.2.67&srpos=47&dliv=none&e=-------en--20--41--txt-txIN-Brisac-------1}}</ref> In 1913, he was elected First Reader in the newly built San Francisco First Church of Christ, Scientist.<ref>{{cite news |title=Christian Scientists Form New Church |publisher=The San Francisco Call |date=November 15, 1913|volume=114(158)|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=SFC19131115.2.40&srpos=20&dliv=none&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-Brisac-------1}}</ref>\n\n===Work with humane organizations===\nBrisac grew up in the waning days of the [[California Gold Rush]] and witnessed the routine abuse of dray horses and mules on San Francisco streets, and he had known about the work of the [[San Francisco SPCA|Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals]] since its founding in 1868. But his involvement with the group didn't begin until, in the aftermath of the earthquake in 1906, he assisted in the rescue of trapped and injured animals and helped build water troughs for the horses used in rescue and reconstruction. He joined the Society in 1907 and was active for the rest of his life, as a member (1907\u20131916), Trustee (1916\u20131930) and President (1930\u20131940). At the time of his death, he was also First Vice-President, formerly President of the State Humane Association of California and Director of the [[American Humane|American Humane Association]] active in American [[Red Star Rescue]] and Animal Relief.<ref name=\"Memorial\">{{cite journal |title=In Memorium: B. F. Brisac |journal=Our Animals (publication of the San Francisco Society of the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals) |date=January 1940 |volume=33 |issue=10}}</ref>\n\n==Family life and later years==\n[[File:AW-BFB-VB c1920.jpg|thumb|B. F. Brisac with daughter [[Virginia Brissac]] (right) and granddaughter [[Ardel Wray]] (left), around 1922.]]\nBrisac married Alice M. Hain in 1878 and they had two children - [[Virginia Brissac|Virginia]], born in 1883, and Belnore Brisac, Jr. born in 1888.\n\nWhen Virginia was nineteen, Brisac and his wife were persuaded by friend and local theatre impresario Reginald Travers to allow her to act professionally.<ref name=\"Clayton\">{{cite journal |last1=Clayton |first1=Merle |title=The Coast Defender: Virginia Brissac |journal=The San Diego Magazine |issue=January 1971 |pages=90\u2013108}}</ref>  She quickly became a headliner on the West Coast Stock theatre circuit and, in April 1906, married an actor she met while on tour in Los Angeles, California. When the marriage failed in 1911,<ref name=\"divorce\">\"Virginia Brissac Granted Divorce\". ''The San Francisco Call'', May 7, 1912, p. 1</ref> Brisac made a home for Virginia's four-year-old daughter, [[Ardel Wray|Ardel]], who lived with them for over ten years before finally rejoining her mother in 1922. Brisac continued to be a surrogate father and mentor to his granddaughter until his death in 1940.{{refn|name=\"Theatre\"|group=lower-alpha|Theatre ran in Brisac's family. As a young girl growing up in Texas, his wife Alice had been interested in acting and passed that interest on to her children.  His brother, Norline - a \"would-be actor\" and sometime stage manager for [[Sarah Bernhardt]]<ref name=\"LILLYLIB\" /> - seeded his niece's interest with autographed photo postcards of famous actors.  Daughter Virginia went on to become the professional stage and screen actress [[Virginia Brissac]] (adopting the original French spelling of the family name for her stage name).  Belnore Brisac, Jr. sang and was involved in occasional amateur theatricals throughout his life, and Virginia's daughter became the Hollywood screenwriter and story editor, [[Ardel Wray]], known for the screenplays for ''[[I Walked with a Zombie]]'', ''[[The Leopard Man]]'' and ''[[Isle of the Dead (film)|Isle of the Dead]]''.  Although supportive, there is no evidence that B. F. Brisac himself had any interest in it.<ref name=\"Estate\" />}}\n\nAlice Brisac died in 1924 after a long illness. B. F. remarried in 1930, and he and his second wife continued living in San Francisco until his death ten years later.\n\n==Death and tribute==\n\nUpon his death on January 6, 1940, the Board of Trustees of The San Francisco Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals paid tribute to Brisac in a resolution which read in part: \u201cHis was a long, full and beneficent life. Kindness for his fellow men and a deep sense of consideration and responsibility for the welfare of helpless creatures were primary precepts upon which he based his conduct and living. As a humanitarian his loss will be felt throughout the entire country.\u201d<ref name=\"Memorial\"/>\n\nHis ashes were interred in the Brisac family niche, along with those of his wife and others in his family, in the Columbarium at the Mt. Olivet Memorial Park in Colma, California outside of San Francisco.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brisac, B.F.}}\n[[Category:People from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Animal welfare and rights in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Antiquary", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and career:HomophoneCorner", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B._F._Brisac"}
{"title_page": "George Distel", "text_new": "{{Infobox State Representative \n| name=George Distel\n| image name=\n| state_house=Ohio\n| state=Ohio\n| district=99th\n| term=February 17, 1999-March 31, 2008\n| preceded=[[Ross Boggs]]\n| succeeded=[[Deborah Newcomb]]\n|birth_date= \n|birth_place=\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| alma_mater=\n| profession=\n| residence=\n| religion=\n| party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|}}\n\n'''George Distel''' is a former member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]], representing the 99th District from 1999\u20132008. He was the Administrator of the Ohio Turnpike Commission.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ohioturnpike.org/about/commission_members/ |title=The Ohio Turnpike Commission: L. George Distel |access-date=2011-01-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227135519/http://www.ohioturnpike.org/about/commission_members/ |archive-date=2010-12-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Executive Director George Distel, 58, of Conneaut, submitted his resignation to the commission board, effective April 1, 2011. Distel, a former Democratic member of the Ohio House, took the job in April 2008 under former Gov. Ted Strickland, a Democrat. Distel said he was not asked to leave. Nor did he ask the Kasich camp if he could stay on. He said he would stay for several months if needed \"for a smooth transition.\" \"In the end, I'm ready to retire,\" the former Ashtabula County commissioner said Friday from his home in Conneaut. \"I've been away from home for a long time. I spent nine years in the legislature, three at the turnpike. I'm tired of packing a suitcase.\" Distel said he would often bunk at his son's home in Strongsville, rather than make the trek from turnpike headquarters in Berea to Conneaut. Distel earned $132,500 last year, along with a $6,000 car allowance.\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Distel, George}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ohio Democrats]]\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-OHRepresentative-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox State Representative \n| name=George Distel\n| image name=\n| state_house=Ohio\n| state=Ohio\n| district=99th\n| term=February 17, 1999-March 31, 2008\n| preceded=[[Ross Boggs]]\n| succeeded=[[Deborah Newcomb]]\n|birth_date= \n|birth_place=\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| alma_mater=\n| profession=\n| residence=\n| religion=\n| party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|}}\n\n'''George Distel''' is a former member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]], representing the 99th District from 1999-2008. He was the Administrator of the Ohio Turnpike Commission.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ohioturnpike.org/about/commission_members/ |title=The Ohio Turnpike Commission: L. George Distel |access-date=2011-01-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227135519/http://www.ohioturnpike.org/about/commission_members/ |archive-date=2010-12-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Executive Director George Distel, 58, of Conneaut, submitted his resignation to the commission board, effective April 1, 2011. Distel, a former Democratic member of the Ohio House, took the job in April 2008 under former Gov. Ted Strickland, a Democrat. Distel said he was not asked to leave. Nor did he ask the Kasich camp if he could stay on. He said he would stay for several months if needed \"for a smooth transition.\" \"In the end, I'm ready to retire,\" the former Ashtabula County commissioner said Friday from his home in Conneaut. \"I've been away from home for a long time. I spent nine years in the legislature, three at the turnpike. I'm tired of packing a suitcase.\" Distel said he would often bunk at his son's home in Strongsville, rather than make the trek from turnpike headquarters in Berea to Conneaut. Distel earned $132,500 last year, along with a $6,000 car allowance.\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Distel, George}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ohio Democrats]]\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-OHRepresentative-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1999-2008 \u2192 1999\u20132008", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Distel"}
{"title_page": "Bob Corbin", "text_new": "{{Infobox State Representative \n| name=Bob Corbin\n| image name=\n| state_house=Ohio\n| state=Ohio\n| district=42nd\n| term=January 2, 1977 \u2013 December 31, 2000\n| preceded=[[Fred Young (Ohio)|Fred Young]]\n| succeeded=[[John White (Ohio politician)|John White]]\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1922|12|8}}\n|birth_place=[[Appleton, Wisconsin]], United States\n|death_date={{Death date and age|2013|2|22|1922|12|8}}\n|death_place=[[Centerville, Ohio]], United States\n|}}\n\n'''Robert L. Corbin''' (December 8, 1922 &ndash; February 22, 2013) was a member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]] from 1977\u20132000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.daytondailynews.com/columns/content/localnews/columns/daily/073006hershey.html|title=William Hershey: Former state rep Corbin unhappy with gubernatorial choices|work=Dayton Daily News|accessdate=9 January 2011}}</ref> He was born in [[Appleton, Wisconsin]] in 1922 before moving to Ohio in 1923. His family settled in [[Dayton, Ohio]] in 1929. He served in the [[United States Army]] in Europe during [[World War II]]. After his military service he received his bachelor's degree from [[Otterbein College]] and worked in the food service business. He served on the Centerville, Ohio city council 2002\u20132006.<ref>[http://americanafestival.org/2012-grand-marshal Robert L. Corbein-2012 Grand Marshal]</ref> His district consisted of a portion of [[Montgomery County, Ohio]]. He was succeeded by John White.\n\nHe died in 2013 at the age of 90.<ref>[http://www.daytondailynews.com/news/news/bob-corbin-former-ohio-house-legislator-wwii-pow-d/nWXLL/ Obituary]</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corbin, Bob}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Ohio city council members]]\n[[Category:Ohio Republicans]]\n[[Category:Otterbein University alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Appleton, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:People from Dayton, Ohio]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:People from Centerville, Ohio]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-OHRepresentative-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox State Representative \n| name=Bob Corbin\n| image name=\n| state_house=Ohio\n| state=Ohio\n| district=42nd\n| term=January 2, 1977 \u2013 December 31, 2000\n| preceded=[[Fred Young (Ohio)|Fred Young]]\n| succeeded=[[John White (Ohio politician)|John White]]\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1922|12|8}}\n|birth_place=[[Appleton, Wisconsin]], United States\n|death_date={{Death date and age|2013|2|22|1922|12|8}}\n|death_place=[[Centerville, Ohio]], United States\n|}}\n\n'''Robert L. Corbin''' (December 8, 1922 &ndash; February 22, 2013) was a member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]] from 1977-2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.daytondailynews.com/columns/content/localnews/columns/daily/073006hershey.html|title=William Hershey: Former state rep Corbin unhappy with gubernatorial choices|work=Dayton Daily News|accessdate=9 January 2011}}</ref> He was born in [[Appleton, Wisconsin]] in 1922 before moving to Ohio in 1923. His family settled in [[Dayton, Ohio]] in 1929. He served in the [[United States Army]] in Europe during [[World War II]]. After his military service he received his bachelor's degree from [[Otterbein College]] and worked in the food service business. He served on the Centerville, Ohio city council 2002-2006.<ref>[http://americanafestival.org/2012-grand-marshal Robert L. Corbein-2012 Grand Marshal]</ref> His district consisted of a portion of [[Montgomery County, Ohio]]. He was succeeded by John White.\n\nHe died in 2013 at the age of 90.<ref>[http://www.daytondailynews.com/news/news/bob-corbin-former-ohio-house-legislator-wwii-pow-d/nWXLL/ Obituary]</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corbin, Bob}}\n[[Cat