{"title_page": "John A. Begala", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder \n|image =\n|imagesize = \n| name=John Begala \n| image name=\n| state_house3=Ohio\n|state3=Ohio\n|term3=January 3, 1977 \u2013 December 31, 1982\n|district3=62nd\n|preceded3=[[Marcus Roberto]]\n|succeeded3=[[Paul Jones (Ohio)|Paul Jones]]\n\n|}}\n\n'''John Begala''' is a former member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.communitysolutions.com/assets/1/AssetManager/ReleaseJohnBegala073008.pdf |title=Rep. John A. Begala (D-Kent) |access-date=2010-06-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716235305/http://www.communitysolutions.com/assets/1/AssetManager/ReleaseJohnBegala073008.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Prior to his election, he was a Councilman-at-Large in Kent, Ohio.  As a member of city council, he was part of a coalition that successfully campaigned to amend the city charter, creating a council-manager form of government.  As a state legislator, he worked primarily on health and social legislation and oversight, authoring legislation on social service planning and nursing home reform.  In the field of senior services, he led initiatives to subsidize geriatric medicine programs in state-supported medical schools and establish a statewide network of multi-purpose senior centers.\n\nAfter his third term, Begala became deputy director and chief of staff at the Ohio Department of Mental Retardation and Disabilities and director of the Ohio Developmental Disabilities Planning Council.  He developed budget initiatives increasing state funding for special education, expanding home and community services, and stabilizing finance of residential facilities.\n\nFrom 1986 until 1998, Begala held executive leadership positions with the Greater Cincinnati Hospital Council, University of Cincinnati Medical Center, and Greater Cleveland's MetroHealth System.  From 1998 to 2005, and again from 2008 through 2014, he was Executive Director of The Center for Community Solutions (formerly Federation for Community Planning), a health, social and economic policy think tank with offices in Cleveland and Columbus, Ohio.  Since 2004, Begala has been a lecturer at Baldwin Wallace University, where in 2013 he was appointed Executive in Residence. Begala currently teaches at The Ohio State University\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Begala, John A.}}\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Ohio Democrats]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-OHRepresentative-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder \n|image =\n|imagesize = \n| name=John Begala \n| image name=\n| state_house3=Ohio\n|state3=Ohio\n|term3=January 3, 1977 \u2013 December 31, 1982\n|district3=62nd\n|preceded3=[[Marcus Roberto]]\n|succeeded3=[[Paul Jones (Ohio)|Paul Jones]]\n\n|}}\n\n'''John Begala''' is a former member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.communitysolutions.com/assets/1/AssetManager/ReleaseJohnBegala073008.pdf |title=Rep. John A. Begala (D-Kent) |access-date=2010-06-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716235305/http://www.communitysolutions.com/assets/1/AssetManager/ReleaseJohnBegala073008.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Prior to his election, he was a Councilman-at-Large in Kent, Ohio.  As a member of city council, he was part of a coalition that successfully campaigned to amend the city charter, creating a council-manager form of government.  As a state legislator, he worked primarily on health and social legislation and oversight, authoring legislation on social service planning and nursing home reform.  In the field of senior services, he led initiatives to subsidize geriatric medicine programs in state-supported medical schools and establish a statewide network of multi-purpose senior centers.\n\nAfter his third term, Begala became deputy director and chief of staff at the Ohio Department of Mental Retardation and Disabilities and director of the Ohio Developmental Disabilities Planning Council.  He developed budget initiatives increasing state funding for special education, expanding home and community services, and stabilizing finance of residential facilities.\n\nFrom 1986 until 1998, Begala held executive leadership positions with the Greater Cincinnati Hospital Council, University of Cincinnati Medical Center, and Greater Cleveland\u2019s MetroHealth System.  From 1998 to 2005, and again from 2008 through 2014, he was Executive Director of The Center for Community Solutions (formerly Federation for Community Planning), a health, social and economic policy think tank with offices in Cleveland and Columbus, Ohio.  Since 2004, Begala has been a Lecturer at Baldwin Wallace University, where in 2013 he was appointed Executive in Residence. Begala currently teaches at The Ohio State University\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Begala, John A.}}\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Ohio Democrats]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-OHRepresentative-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: Lecturer \u2192 lecturer, \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_A._Begala"}
{"title_page": "Vermel Whalen", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder \n| name=Vermel Whalen\n| image name=\n| state_house=Ohio\n| state=Ohio\n| district=12th\n| term=1986\u20131998\n| preceded=[[John D. Thompson, Jr.]]\n| succeeded=[[John E. Barnes, Jr.]]\n|birth_name=Vermel Marie Scott\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1928|6|28}}\n|birth_place=[[Portageville, Missouri]]\n| death_date={{death date and age|2013|3|13|1928|6|28}}\n| death_place=[[Cleveland, Ohio]]\n| alma_mater=\n| profession=\n| residence= \n| religion=\n| party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|}}\n'''Vermel Marie Whalen''' (n\u00e9e '''Scott'''; June 28, 1928 &ndash; March 13, 2013) was a member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]], serving a [[Cleveland]] area district from 1986\u20131998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.georgewashingtonwilliams.org/Legislators.aspx?letter%3DW%26publicOfficialId%3D90 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 9, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716153148/http://www.georgewashingtonwilliams.org/Legislators.aspx?letter=W&publicOfficialId=90 |archivedate=July 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nWhelan was born in [[Portageville, Missouri]] and went to the local high school there. She moved to Cleveland, Ohio. Whelan went to [[Dyke College]], [[University of Georgia]], and [[Cleveland State University]] where she received her certificates. Whelan served as a nurse in Cleveland. She was the administrator of the Comprehensive Employment and Training Act for the city of Cleveland. Whelan also served as assistant administrator for the city recreation department. She died in 2013 of cancer in Cleveland, Ohio.<ref>[http://www.cleveland.com/obituaries/index.ssf/2013/03/vermel_m_whalen_spent_12_years.html Vermel M. Whelan spent 12 years in the Ohio House: new obituary]</ref><ref>[http://www.memorialsolutions.com/sitemaker/sites/BROWNF2/obit.cgi?user=956148Whalen In Memoriam Vermel M. Whelan]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110716153148/http://www.georgewashingtonwilliams.org/Legislators.aspx?letter=W&publicOfficialId=90 Profile from George Washington Williams ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071110235500/http://www.choicemidwives.org/?page_id=18 Choice Legislation]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whalen, Vermel}}\n[[Category:Women state legislators in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Ohio Democrats]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:People from Portageville, Missouri]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:American nurses]]\n[[Category:American women nurses]]\n[[Category:Cleveland State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Georgia alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Ohio]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder \n| name=Vermel Whalen\n| image name=\n| state_house=Ohio\n| state=Ohio\n| district=12th\n| term=1986\u20131998\n| preceded=[[John D. Thompson, Jr.]]\n| succeeded=[[John E. Barnes, Jr.]]\n|birth_name=Vermel Marie Scott\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1928|6|28}}\n|birth_place=[[Portageville, Missouri]]\n| death_date={{death date and age|2013|3|13|1928|6|28}}\n| death_place=[[Cleveland, Ohio]]\n| alma_mater=\n| profession=\n| residence= \n| religion=\n| party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|}}\n'''Vermel Marie Whalen''' (n\u00e9e '''Scott'''; June 28, 1928 &ndash; March 13, 2013) was a member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]], serving a [[Cleveland]] area district from 1986-1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.georgewashingtonwilliams.org/Legislators.aspx?letter%3DW%26publicOfficialId%3D90 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 9, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716153148/http://www.georgewashingtonwilliams.org/Legislators.aspx?letter=W&publicOfficialId=90 |archivedate=July 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nWhelan was born in [[Portageville, Missouri]] and went to the local high school there. She moved to Cleveland, Ohio. Whelan went to [[Dyke College]], [[University of Georgia]], and [[Cleveland State University]] where she received her certificates. Whelan served as a nurse in Cleveland. She was the administrator of the Comprehensive Employment and Training Act for the city of Cleveland. Whelan also served as assistant administrator for the city recreation department. She died in 2013 of cancer in Cleveland, Ohio.<ref>[http://www.cleveland.com/obituaries/index.ssf/2013/03/vermel_m_whalen_spent_12_years.html Vermel M. Whelan spent 12 years in the Ohio House: new obituary]</ref><ref>[http://www.memorialsolutions.com/sitemaker/sites/BROWNF2/obit.cgi?user=956148Whalen In Memoriam Vermel M. Whelan]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110716153148/http://www.georgewashingtonwilliams.org/Legislators.aspx?letter=W&publicOfficialId=90 Profile from George Washington Williams ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071110235500/http://www.choicemidwives.org/?page_id=18 Choice Legislation]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whalen, Vermel}}\n[[Category:Women state legislators in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Members of the Ohio House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Ohio Democrats]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:People from Portageville, Missouri]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:American nurses]]\n[[Category:American women nurses]]\n[[Category:Cleveland State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Georgia alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Ohio]]\n\n\n{{Ohio-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1986-1998 \u2192 1986\u20131998", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vermel_Whalen"}
